def parse_general_row_info(data: pd.DataFrame ,row_name: str, sep: str, column_parser: dict, useful_columns: list):
    data_expanded = data[row_name].str.split(sep, expand=True)
    data_expanded.rename(columns=column_parser, inplace=True)
    for i in range(len(useful_columns)):
        data[useful_columns[i]] = data_expanded[useful_columns[i]]
    data.drop(columns=[row_name], inplace=True)

def clean_values(data: pd.DataFrame, columns_to_replace: list):
    data[columns_to_replace] = data[columns_to_replace].replace(
        to_replace=r"[^\d\.\-]",  # keep digits, dot, and negative sign altho the data seems to be non-negative 
        value='',
        regex=True
    ).apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='coerce')

births_by_age_and_edu = pd.read_csv("estat_demo_faeduc.tsv", sep='\t') #unit = number 

countries_with_data = ['EL', 'LT', 'PT', 'ES', 'RO', 'CZ', 'HU', 'SI', 'DK', 'HR', 'SK', 'IT', 'FI', 'SE', 'PL', 'NO']
years_to_process = ['Y15', 'Y16', 'Y17', 'Y18', 'Y19', 'Y20', 'Y21', 'Y22', 'Y23', 'Y24', 'Y25', 'Y26', 'Y27', 'Y28', 'Y29', 'Y30', 'Y31', 'Y32', 'Y33', 'Y34', 'Y35', 'Y36', 'Y37', 'Y38', 'Y39', 'Y40', 'Y41', 'Y42', 'Y43', 'Y44', 'Y45', 'Y46']
years_to_ignore = [str(year) for year in range(2007, 2022)] + ['2023']

parse_general_row_info(data=births_by_age_and_edu, 
                      row_name='freq,unit,age,isced11,geo\TIME_PERIOD',
                      sep=',',
                      column_parser={0: 'freq', 1: 'unit', 2: 'age', 3: 'edu', 4: 'geo'},
                      useful_columns= ['age', 'edu', 'geo'])

clean_values(births_by_age_and_edu, births_by_age_and_edu.columns[:-3])
births_by_age_and_edu.columns = births_by_age_and_edu.columns.str.strip()

births_by_age_and_edu = births_by_age_and_edu[
                        (births_by_age_and_edu['edu']).isin(['ED0-2', 'ED3_4', 'ED5-8']) &
                        (births_by_age_and_edu['geo'].isin(countries_with_data)) &
                        (births_by_age_and_edu['age'].isin(years_to_process))].copy()

births_by_age_and_edu = births_by_age_and_edu.drop(columns=years_to_ignore)
births_by_age_and_edu.rename(columns={'2022': 'births'}, inplace=True)

births_by_age_and_edu['age_num'] = births_by_age_and_edu['age'].str.extract(r'Y(\d+)').astype(int)

# analyzing patterns across countries, we need to average across them
births_by_age_and_edu_groupped = births_by_age_and_edu.groupby(['age_num', 'edu']).agg({'births': 'sum' }).reset_index()

births_total_by_age = births_by_age_and_edu_groupped.groupby('age_num')['births'].sum().reset_index()
births_total_by_age.rename(columns={'births': 'births_total'}, inplace=True)

births_by_age_and_edu_groupped = births_by_age_and_edu_groupped.merge(births_total_by_age, on='age_num')

# age distribution of births by education level
births_by_age_and_edu_groupped['perc_births'] = (births_by_age_and_edu_groupped['births'] / births_by_age_and_edu_groupped['births_total']) * 100

# print(births_by_age_and_edu_groupped[births_by_age_and_edu_groupped['births'].isna()])

# Euro per inhabitant : This means the amount of money is divided by the population.
# Inflation is the general rise in prices over time. So, a euro in 2024 buys less than it did in 2015.
# The amount of money per person, adjusted for inflation, so that the values are all expressed in terms of what money was worth in 2015.

ax = sns.barplot(data=employment_birth_rates, x='geo', y='2022', hue='n_child', palette=['#FF9F00', '#90D1CA', '#C68EFD'] )

xticks = ax.get_xticks() # current positions of the bars
countries = employment_birth_rates['geo'].unique() # order of the countries 
n_child_order = sorted(employment_birth_rates['n_child'].unique())

bar_width = 0.8 / len(['0', '1', '2'])  # adjusting bar width based on number of hues

# drawing the red lines 
for geo in countries:
    for i, n_child in enumerate(['0', '1', '2']):
        row = employment_birth_rates[(employment_birth_rates['geo'] == geo) & (employment_birth_rates['n_child'] == n_child)]
        if not row.empty:
            geo_idx = np.where(countries == geo)[0][0]
            x = xticks[geo_idx] - 0.4 + i * bar_width + bar_width / 2 
            y = row['2015'].values[0]
            ax.plot([x - bar_width / 2, x + bar_width / 2 ], [y, y], color='red', linewidth=3, linestyle='dashed')

def print_corr_change(data, employment_change_col, fertility_change_col='fertility_change'):
    r, p = pearsonr(data[employment_change_col], data[fertility_change_col])
    print(f"{employment_change_col} ↔ {fertility_change_col}: r = {r:.2f}, p = {p:.4f}")

print("Correlations: ")
for col in ['employment_change_0child', 'employment_change_1child', 'employment_change_2child']:
    print_corr_change(employment_birth_rates, col)

benefits_fertility = pd.merge(benefits_total, fertility_birth_rates, on='geo')
benefits_fertility['rate_improvement'] = benefits_fertility['fertility_rate_2022'] - benefits_fertility['fertility_rate_2015']
benefits_fertility['geo'] = benefits_fertility['geo'].map(countries_mapper)

benefits_fertility_improved = benefits_fertility[benefits_fertility['rate_improvement'] >=0]
benefits_fertility_decreased = benefits_fertility[benefits_fertility['rate_improvement'] < 0]

TOP_CATEGORIES = 8

# improved fertility
avg_benefit_by_type_improved = benefits_fertility_improved.groupby('benefit_type')['2022'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False)
values_improved = avg_benefit_by_type_improved.tolist()[:TOP_CATEGORIES] + [sum(avg_benefit_by_type_improved[TOP_CATEGORIES:])]
labels_improved = list(avg_benefit_by_type_improved.index[:TOP_CATEGORIES]) + ['others']

# decreased fertility
avg_benefit_by_type_decreased = benefits_fertility_decreased.groupby('benefit_type')['2022'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False)
values_decreased = avg_benefit_by_type_decreased.tolist()[:TOP_CATEGORIES] + [sum(avg_benefit_by_type_decreased[TOP_CATEGORIES:])]

# aggregate total benefits per country and fertility rates for 2015 and 2022
total_benefits_2015 = benefits_fertility.groupby('geo')['2015'].sum().reset_index().rename(columns={'2015': 'total_benefits_2015'})
total_benefits_2022 = benefits_fertility.groupby('geo')['2022'].sum().reset_index().rename(columns={'2022': 'total_benefits_2022'})
fertility_rates_2015 = benefits_fertility[['geo', 'fertility_rate_2015']].drop_duplicates()
fertility_rates_2022 = benefits_fertility[['geo', 'fertility_rate_2022']].drop_duplicates()

benefits_and_fertility_2015 = total_benefits_2015.merge(fertility_rates_2015, on='geo')
benefits_and_fertility_2022 = total_benefits_2022.merge(fertility_rates_2022, on='geo')

plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))

# plot 2015 
plt.scatter(benefits_and_fertility_2015['total_benefits_2015'], benefits_and_fertility_2015['fertility_rate_2015'],
            color='purple', s=100, alpha=0.7, label='2015')

# plot 2022 
plt.scatter(benefits_and_fertility_2022['total_benefits_2022'], benefits_and_fertility_2022['fertility_rate_2022'],
            color='orange', s=100, alpha=0.7, label='2022')

sns.regplot(x='total_benefits_2022', y='fertility_rate_2022', data=benefits_and_fertility_2022,
            scatter=False, color='darkorange', line_kws={'linewidth': 2})

plt.title('Total Benefits and Fertility Rate (2015, 2022)', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Total Family Benefits', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Fertility Rate', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
